 In my tests blake2b-256 was far better than Keccak-256.\n\nBetter seed spread-out to all state words, not just a part of the first, could definitely help some failing tests. Or longer seeds, of the same size as the state. But then we would need to filter out bad initial states, which could corrupt the function even more. That's why I didn't do that. The other idea with crypto tests is to leave out the seeding and related tests.  This would e.g. need to change MomentChi2 from iterating the seeds to the key, and all the new collision tests.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574702068,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDMxNDgwMjk4MA=="},"target":"efc027cb0814254c219d753c82c0dd5a948e5b7a872b24aebbdb8b8532574c16","message":"This is about the results of the new crypto branch. And it's new CRYPTO paragraph in the docs. https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/tree/crypto#crypto\n\nI'm sure about the failing tests and the weakness, but I'm not sure about the cryptographic applicability.  It involves changes in the first 32bit state word (the seed), which is not used and not tested in crypto. In my understanding weak state mixings point to a weak function. Crypto just deals with weak keys or timing, the state is fixed. We are testing the reverse here. Anyway, the functions itself are weak, as state changes should affect the function quality as measured.\nMaybe Yann's new collision tests (from March) are buggy, but so far they stood the test of time very well.\n\nFor now it's not recommended to use them as hash table functions when capped to lower bits. When using them with all bits it should be still strong, but maybe the GRU or NSA are exploiting low bit weaknesses already.\n\nAnd the NIST test suite needs to be open source. Otherwise all their claims and recommendations are not trustworthy. In my tests blake2b-256 was far better than Keccak-256.\n\nBetter seed spread-out to all state words, not just a part of the first, could definitely help some failing tests. Or longer seeds, of the same size as the state. But then we would need to filter out bad initial states, which could corrupt the function even more. That's why I didn't do that. The other idea with crypto tests is to leave out the seeding and related tests.  This would e.g. need to change MomentChi2 from iterating the seeds to the key, and all the new collision tests.","files":null},{"type":5,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574698812,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOkxhYmVsZWRFdmVudDI4Mjg3NDIwMTM="},"added":["docs"],"removed":[]},{"type":5,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574698827,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOkxhYmVsZWRFdmVudDI4Mjg3NDI5OTY="},"added":["question"],"removed":[]},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"173f4fceac25ce053a133bd829b18be7ad10b908"},"timestamp":1574700262,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1ODIzMTIzNQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/87#issuecomment-558231235"},"message":"@Cyan4973?","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"173f4fceac25ce053a133bd829b18be7ad10b908"},"timestamp":1574700262,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDMxNDc4MjU2MQ=="},"target":"b3ed45947719d7ab191b0fe7f97b94eca87579ff2ff524a2bc71e1a9ee6c40b5","message":"\u003e In my understanding weak state mixings point to a weak function.\n\n+1\n\n\u003e Crypto just deals with weak keys or timing, the state is fixed.\n\u003e We are testing the reverse here. Anyway, the functions itself are weak, as state changes should affect the function quality as measured.\n\n+1\n\nBut...\n - Most functions performs a \"compression\" data into the state.\n - The compression step can be designed to exclude the possibility of changing the state in a certain way. For example, for any input, it may not be possible to change less than N bits of state, where N may be significantly greater than 1.\n - Thus, some tests exploiting a minor state change may not be correct for evaluating the entire function as a whole.\n\nHowever, this is a rather unexpected for me weakness. I. e. I did not assume that the resulting statistical skew would be so significant.\n\n\u003e Maybe Yann's new collision tests (from March) are buggy, but so far they stood the test of time very well.\n@Cyan4973?","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"173f4fceac25ce053a133bd829b18be7ad10b908"},"timestamp":1574700345,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDMxNDc4MzU3MQ=="},"target":"b3ed45947719d7ab191b0fe7f97b94eca87579ff2ff524a2bc71e1a9ee6c40b5","message":"\u003e In my understanding weak state mixings point to a weak function.\n\n+1\n\n\u003e Crypto just deals with weak keys or timing, the state is fixed.\n\u003e We are testing the reverse here. Anyway, the functions itself are weak, as state changes should affect the function quality as measured.\n\n+1\n\nBut...\n - Most functions performs a \"compression\" data into the state.\n - The compression step can be designed to exclude the possibility of changing the state in a certain way. For example, for any input, it may be impossible to change less than N bits of state, where N may be significantly greater than 1.\n - Thus, some tests exploiting a minor state change may not be correct for evaluating the entire function as a whole.\n\nHowever, this is a rather unexpected for me weakness. I. e. I did not assume that the resulting statistical skew would be so significant.\n\n\u003e Maybe Yann's new collision tests (from March) are buggy, but so far they stood the test of time very well.\n@Cyan4973?","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"173f4fceac25ce053a133bd829b18be7ad10b908"},"timestamp":1574700381,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDMxNDc4NDAwOA=="},"target":"b3ed45947719d7ab191b0fe7f97b94eca87579ff2ff524a2bc71e1a9ee6c40b5","message":"\u003e In my understanding weak state mixings point to a weak function.\n\n+1\n\n\u003e Crypto just deals with weak keys or timing, the state is fixed.\n\u003e We are testing the reverse here. Anyway, the functions itself are weak, as state changes should affect the function quality as measured.\n\n+1\n\nBut...\n - Most functions performs a \"compression\" data into the state.\n - The compression step can be designed to exclude the possibility of changing the state in a certain way. For example, for any input block, it may be impossible to change less than N bits of state, where N may be significantly greater than 1.\n - Thus, some tests exploiting a minor state change may not be correct for evaluating the entire function as a whole.\n\nHowever, this is a rather unexpected for me weakness. I. e. I did not assume that the resulting statistical skew would be so significant.\n\n\u003e Maybe Yann's new collision tests (from March) are buggy, but so far they stood the test of time very well.\n@Cyan4973?","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"173f4fceac25ce053a133bd829b18be7ad10b908"},"timestamp":1574700413,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDMxNDc4NDM3Ng=="},"target":"b3ed45947719d7ab191b0fe7f97b94eca87579ff2ff524a2bc71e1a9ee6c40b5","message":"\u003e In my understanding weak state mixings point to a weak function.\n\n+1\n\n\u003e Crypto just deals with weak keys or timing, the state is fixed.\n\u003e We are testing the reverse here. Anyway, the functions itself are weak, as state changes should affect the function quality as measured.\n\n+1\n\nBut...\n - Most functions performs a \"compression\" data into the state.\n - The compression step can be designed to exclude the possibility of changing the state in a certain way. For example, for any _single_ input block, it may be impossible to change less than N bits of state, where N may be significantly greater than 1.\n - Thus, some tests exploiting a minor state change may not be correct for evaluating the entire function as a whole.\n\nHowever, this is a rather unexpected for me weakness. I. e. I did not assume that the resulting statistical skew would be so significant.\n\n\u003e Maybe Yann's new collision tests (from March) are buggy, but so far they stood the test of time very well.\n@Cyan4973?","files":null},{"type":2,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574699069,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE3OlJlbmFtZWRUaXRsZUV2ZW50MjgyODc1OTEyMw=="},"title":"Crypto tests. Q: Are you sure? (\"secure quality crypto hash functions are actually statistically extremely weak\")","was":"Crypto tests. Q: Are you sure? (\"secure quality crypto hash functions are actually statistically extremely weak\")"},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1574700170,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1ODIzOTA2MQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/87#issuecomment-558239061"},"message":"I think it's a bug.\n\n```C\nstatic\tinline\tvoid\twysha(const\tvoid\t*key,\tint\tlen,\tunsigned\tseed,\tvoid *out) {\n\tuint64_t\ts[4]={wyhash(key,len,seed+0),wyhash(key,len,seed+1),wyhash(key,len,seed+2),wyhash(key,len,seed+3)};\n\tmemcpy(out,\ts,\t32);\n}\n```\n\n```\nKeyset 'Sparse' - 32-bit keys with up to 7 bits set - 4514873 keys\nTesting collisions (256-bit)     - Expected          0.0, actual      0 (0.00x)\nTesting collisions (high 128-bit) - Expected          0.0, actual      0 (0.00x)\nTesting collisions (high 64-bit) - Expected          0.0, actual      0 (0.00x)\nTesting collisions (high 32-bit) - Expected       4746.0, actual   2386 (0.50x)\nTesting collisions (high 26-39 bits) - Worst is 38 bits: 39/74 (0.53x)\nTesting collisions (high 12-bit) - Expected    4514873.0, actual 4510777 (1.00x) (-4096)\nTesting collisions (high  8-bit) - Expected    4514873.0, actual 4514617 (1.00x) (-256)\nTesting collisions (low  128-bit) - Expected          0.0, actual 4514872 (75369200179260515463276265472000.00x) (4514872) !!!!!\nTesting collisions (low  64-bit) - Expected          0.0, actual 4514872 (4085772528642.46x) (4514872) !!!!!\nTesting collisions (low  32-bit) - Expected       4746.0, actual 4514872 (951.29x) (4510126) !!!!!\nTesting collisions (low  26-39 bits) - Worst is 39 bits: 4514872/37 (121765.51x) !!!!!\nTesting collisions (low  12-bit) - Expected    4514873.0, actual 4514872 (1.00x) (-1)\nTesting collisions (low   8-bit) - Expected    4514873.0, actual 4514872 (1.00x) (-1)\nTesting distribution - Worst bias is the 19-bit window at bit 38 - 0.064%\n\n```","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574700875,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1ODI0NDIxNw==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/87#issuecomment-558244217"},"message":"@wangyi-fudan In the new collisions test?","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574701115,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1ODI0NjA0OQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/87#issuecomment-558246049"},"message":"BTW: I will not merge this new CRYPTO README paragraph, until we can agree on it's interpretation and wording. Maybe it's just a test bug. Maybe the tests should emphasize more on the key and less on the seed, and leave the seed asis.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1574702026,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1ODI1MjQ1OA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/87#issuecomment-558252458"},"message":"\u003e \n\u003e \n\u003e @wangyi-fudan In the new collisions test?\n\nyes, I downloaded your lastest crypto branch. you can test it by yourself, super easy.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"173f4fceac25ce053a133bd829b18be7ad10b908"},"timestamp":1574702781,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1ODI1NjcyNA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/87#issuecomment-558256724"},"message":"@rurban:\n - for Keccak it is correct to poke a seed into the `capacity` part of state, but NOT into the `rate` (since it is equals to XOR with a subsequent input).\n - for MD5, SHA1, SHA2 and BLAKE2b it is correct to poke a seed into any part of the state.\n\nSo, seems it is a bug in the test(s).","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"173f4fceac25ce053a133bd829b18be7ad10b908"},"timestamp":1574702781,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDMxNDgxMDYzMA=="},"target":"b3cc14d16b4dd2ff586518d5c7c90df5cfff29d24c332d94437d11c6987f8867","message":"@rurban:\n - for Keccak it is correct to poke a seed into the `capacity` part of state, but NOT into the `rate` (since it is equals to XOR with a subsequent input).\n - for MD5, SHA1, SHA2 and BLAKE2b it is correct to poke a seed into any part of the state.\n\nThis may explain the reason that Keccak looks worse.\nHowever, seems it is a bug in the test(s).","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574707631,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1ODI3MDgxOQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/87#issuecomment-558270819"},"message":"I agree with WangYi, the testLowBits part in `TestHashList` is broken. I wrote that, not Yann.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574707631,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDMxNDg1NzcyNg=="},"target":"40f345b7310fc051af2b61c03f3c79fdcff3fe367dd89134a29272f7460b4de3","message":"I agree with WangYi, the testLowBits part in `TestHashList` is broken. I wrote that, not Yann. In detail `bitreverse`.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574769906,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDU1ODU5MDAzNw==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/87#issuecomment-558590037"},"message":"I've deleted now this obsolete CRYPTO paragraph, as I found and fixed the test bug. It was an underflow with hashtypes \u003e 64bit, as operator |= was only defined for int, not anything larger, thus zeroextending it silently.\nUpdating the wrong tests will need a few days.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574769906,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDMxNTMyMzUzNg=="},"target":"c187bbd0d8e666e6c396a70ee51cefd5f539170b8666ac22bcc72f05c0cc12a4","message":"I've deleted now this obsolete CRYPTO paragraph, as I found and fixed the test bug. It was an underflow with hashtypes \u003e 64bit, as operator |= in bitreverse was only defined for int, not anything larger, thus zeroextending it silently. Which caused hashes collide to 0, as the low bits were produced by bitreversing the hashes, and left shift.\nUpdating the wrong tests will need a few days.","files":null},{"type":4,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1574768168,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDExOkNsb3NlZEV2ZW50MjgzMTU2NTM5Mg=="},"status":2}]}